          "id": "ai-3",
          "title": "Codex will soon be able to control other desktop devices via Computer Use",
          "link": "https://www.testingcatalog.com/openai-will-let-codex-control-other-desktop-devices-via-computer-use/",
          "image": "https://storage.ghost.io/c/2a/1b/2a1b1782-8506-4d7d-bf53-ad3fb52e2a0f/content/images/size/w1200/2026/05/Screenshot-2026-05-16-at-16.44.42.webp",
          "source": "TestingCatalog",
          "tags": [
            "ai",
            "agents",
            "macos"
          ],
          "description": "OpenAI is working on a capability that lets its coding agent operate macOS applications through Computer Use even when a laptop is locked or asleep. Computer Use currently requires an unlocked, awake session to see the screen, move the cursor, and type. Lifting the restriction will allow users to direct their agents without having to walk back to their machines to log in first. It is unknown when the feature will be released.",
          "one-liner": "OpenAI is developing a \"Computer Use\" feature for its Codex agent to control macOS applications on locked or asleep laptops, potentially bypassing current security restrictions.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "OpenAI is working on an extension for its Codex agent's \"Computer Use\" capability that would allow it to operate macOS applications remotely even when the laptop is locked or asleep, addressing a limitation of its May 14 mobile app remote control feature.",
            "why": "This represents a significant step towards more autonomous AI agents capable of continuous background operation on personal devices, raising questions about device security and user control."
          },
          "deep-summary": "* OpenAI is extending its Codex remote control system to allow operation of macOS applications even when the laptop is locked or asleep.\n* Currently, \"Computer Use\" requires an unlocked, awake session to interact with the screen.\n* The new development aims to lift this restriction, enabling users to direct their agents from a phone without needing to log in to the machine.\n* This feature follows the May 14 release of a remote control in the ChatGPT mobile app for Mac.\n* The article notes that Anthropic's Claude Code has a similar phone-to-machine control but is also constrained by locked Macs.\n* There are open questions about how Apple will react to a feature that bypasses macOS security defaults for locked screens.\n* OpenAI is also exploring connecting to and controlling multiple desktop devices running the Codex app.\n* Release timing for this enhanced capability is currently unknown.",
          "decoder": "* **Codex**: An AI model from OpenAI primarily designed to translate natural language into code and perform programming-related tasks.\n* **Computer Use**: A feature within OpenAI's ecosystem that allows an AI agent to see and interact with a computer's screen, cursor, and applications.",
          "rating": 4,
          "content-template-path": "full-content/2026-05-18/ai-3"
        },
        {
          "id": "ai-4",
          "title": "AI economics part 2",
          "link": "https://x.com/sriramkri/status/2054594308494229882",
          "source": "Sriram Krishnan (X)",
          "tags": [
            "ai",
            "hardware",
            "infrastructure"
          ],
          "description": "AI labs are in an ongoing war over GPU resources. That article looks into demand and supply and how the infrastructure powering AI today may not be sufficient. Scaling GPUs doesn't scale compute linearly. Efficiency matters more at raw scale given finite supply.",
          "one-liner": "AI labs are engaged in an intense \"GPU war\" due to finite supply, where scaling GPUs does not linearly increase compute and efficiency becomes paramount.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "The article discusses the ongoing competition among AI labs for GPU resources, highlighting that the demand for GPUs far outstrips supply and that simply adding more GPUs does not guarantee a linear increase in computational power.",
            "why": "This illustrates the critical bottleneck in AI development, emphasizing that hardware and infrastructure limitations are a major factor in the industry's growth and the increasing importance of software and architectural efficiency in utilizing scarce resources."
          },
          "rating": 4
        },
        {
          "id": "ai-5",
          "title": "Portability Is a Myth: Why the Best AI Stacks Will Never Be Hardware-Agnostic",
          "link": "https://x.com/PatrickToulme/status/2055709800986780028",
          "source": "Patrick Toulme (X)",
          "tags": [
            "ai",
            "hardware",
            "research"
          ],
          "description": "AI kernel portability is structurally impossible because TPU's Pallas, NVIDIA's CuTile and CUTLASS, AWS's NKI, AMD's FlyDSL, and Tenstorrent's tt-Metalium each expose hardware-specific concepts that no universal DSL can unify. The evidence: MaxText's MoE grouped matmul ships as 282 lines of Pallas on TPU while flashinfer's equivalent for Blackwell SM100 takes 4 million lines of generated CUDA, with zero shared code because the algorithms themselves diverge across hardware.",
          "one-liner": "AI kernel portability is fundamentally impossible across different hardware like TPUs and NVIDIA GPUs because their specialized domain-specific languages expose unique architectural concepts.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "Patrick Toulme's post argues that AI kernel portability is a myth because hardware-specific DSLs like TPU's Pallas, NVIDIA's CuTile/CUTLASS, AWS's NKI, AMD's FlyDSL, and Tenstorrent's tt-Metalium expose distinct hardware concepts, making universal unification impossible.",
            "why": "This challenges the common assumption of hardware abstraction in software development, suggesting that high-performance AI will remain deeply tied to specific hardware architectures and require specialized engineering, driving vendor lock-in and differentiated performance.",
            "takeaway": "Developers building high-performance AI systems should be aware that optimizing for one hardware platform often means sacrificing portability and investing deeply in its specific programming model."
          },
          "deep-summary": "* The article asserts that AI kernel portability across different hardware platforms is structurally impossible.\n* This is attributed to each hardware vendor exposing unique, hardware-specific concepts through their domain-specific languages (DSLs).\n* Examples of these DSLs include Pallas for TPUs, CuTile and CUTLASS for NVIDIA GPUs, NKI for AWS, FlyDSL for AMD, and tt-Metalium for Tenstorrent.\n* The author argues that no universal DSL can unify these disparate hardware concepts.\n* As evidence, the article cites MaxText's MoE grouped matmul, which requires 282 lines of Pallas on TPU.\n* In contrast, Flashinfer's equivalent for NVIDIA Blackwell SM100 requires 4 million lines of generated CUDA.\n* The key takeaway is that these implementations have zero shared code because the underlying algorithms diverge significantly across hardware.\n* This implies that achieving peak performance on AI hardware necessitates deep, platform-specific optimization rather than relying on hardware-agnostic solutions.",
          "decoder": "* **AI kernel**: A fundamental, optimized computational routine that performs a specific operation within an AI model, often executed directly on specialized hardware.\n* **Domain-specific language (DSL)**: A programming language tailored for a particular application domain, offering specific constructs and optimizations relevant to that domain, such as hardware acceleration.\n* **Pallas**: A DSL used for programming Google's Tensor Processing Units (TPUs).\n* **CuTile / CUTLASS**: Libraries and frameworks from NVIDIA for high-performance linear algebra and matrix computations on their CUDA-enabled GPUs.\n* **NKI**: AWS's internal kernel interface, likely for their custom AI accelerators.\n* **FlyDSL**: AMD's domain-specific language for programming their AI hardware.\n* **tt-Metalium**: Tenstorrent's specialized software stack for their AI accelerators.\n* **MoE grouped matmul**: Mixture-of-Experts grouped matrix multiplication, a common operation in large AI models, particularly those using sparse architectures.\n* **Flashinfer**: A high-performance inference library for large language models, often optimized for NVIDIA GPUs.",
          "rating": 5
        },
        {
          "id": "ai-6",
          "title": "Tokenomics: the 62.5-minute rule for Claude's cache",
          "link": "https://skids.dev/blog/anthropic-cache-tokenomics/",
          "image": "https://skids.dev/og/anthropic-cache-tokenomics.png",
          "source": "skids.dev",
          "tags": [
            "ai",
            "llm",
            "backend",
            "performance"
          ],
          "description": "If you expect to need a cache before 62.5 minutes, refresh it. Otherwise, let it expire. This number stays the same between models, and it doesn't change, no matter the size of the cache. The amount of dollars may change, but the decision point is still the same.",
          "one-liner": "To optimize Anthropic Claude's cache costs, refresh a prompt cache if you expect to use it again within 62.5 minutes, otherwise let it expire and rewrite.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "The article details a \"62.5-minute rule\" for Anthropic's Claude prompt cache: refresh it if needed before 62.5 minutes, otherwise let it expire. This timing is independent of model (Opus, Sonnet, Haiku) or prefix size, though dollar costs vary.",
            "why": "This provides a practical, data-driven guideline for optimizing LLM API costs by strategically managing cache refreshes versus rewrites, highlighting how even minor API features require careful cost-benefit analysis at scale.",
            "takeaway": "When using Anthropic's Claude API with prompt caching, implement logic to refresh caches that are likely to be used within the next 62.5 minutes to save costs, and consider the 10:1 compression ratio rule for context compaction."
          },
          "deep-summary": "* Anthropic's prompt caching for Claude models has specific pricing tiers: 5-minute cache write (1.25x base input price), 1-hour cache write (2x), and cache read/refresh (0.10x).\n* A cache hit also refreshes the Time-To-Live (TTL) to 5 minutes, making \"keep-alive\" requests viable.\n* The break-even point for refreshing a cache versus letting it expire and rewriting it is exactly 62.5 minutes.\n* This 62.5-minute rule holds true across all Claude models (Opus, Sonnet, Haiku) and for various cached prefix sizes (e.g., 5K to 500K tokens).\n* The cost calculation (Write cost divided by Read cost) simplifies to 1.25 / 0.10 = 12.5, which, when multiplied by the 5-minute refresh interval, yields 62.5 minutes.\n* While the decision point remains constant, the dollar savings (or losses) from optimal cache management are larger for more expensive models like Opus and larger prefix sizes.\n* The article also highlights \"cache footguns\": Opus 4.7 uses a new tokenizer that can make text up to 35% larger in token count; small prefixes (under 4096 for Opus, 1024 for Sonnet) don't cache; and the lookback window for cache hits is 20 content blocks.\n* Context compaction, where an agent summarizes a conversation to reduce token count, is also analyzed. A 10:1 compression ratio is roughly optimal, breaking even in about 8 future turns.\n* Compacting context incurs costs for reading old tokens, generating summary output tokens (5x base price), and writing the new summary to cache.\n* A key caution is that a verbose summary or a summary that omits crucial details can negate cost savings or even lead to quality degradation.\n* The 62.5-minute rule assumes future use; if many sessions are single-question, no caching might be cheaper.",
          "decoder": "* **Tokenomics**: The economic principles governing the use and cost of \"tokens\" within an AI model's operation, including pricing for input, output, and caching.\n* **Prompt cache**: A feature offered by some LLM APIs (like Anthropic's Claude) that stores frequently used parts of a prompt (a \"prefix\") to reduce repeated input token costs.\n* **Prefix**: The initial, often static or frequently repeated, part of a prompt that can be cached.\n* **Time-To-Live (TTL)**: A mechanism that sets an expiration time for a cached item; after this time, the item is considered stale and removed or needs to be refreshed.\n* **Context compaction**: The process of reducing the length of a conversation or historical context provided to an LLM, typically by summarizing it, to save on token costs and manage context window limits.\n* **Opus / Sonnet / Haiku**: Different models within Anthropic's Claude family, offering varying levels of capability and cost.",
          "rating": 5,
          "content-template-path": "full-content/2026-05-18/ai-6"
        },
        {
          "id": "ai-7",
          "title": "How Claude Code works in large codebases: Best practices and where to start",
          "link": "https://claude.com/blog/how-claude-code-works-in-large-codebases-best-practices-and-where-to-start",
          "image": "https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/68a44d4040f98a4adf2207b6/6a060215e86f555c3638a2a1_og_how-claude-code-works-in-large-codebases-best-practices-and-where-to-start.jpg",
          "source": "Claude Blog",
          "tags": [
            "ai",
            "enterprise",
            "devops",
            "backend"
          ],
          "description": "Claude Code is now being used in production across multiple large codebases in organizations with thousands of developers. These environments bring challenges that smaller codebases don't. This article covers patterns that Anthropic has seen that have led to the successful adoption of Claude Code at scale. It looks at how Claude Code has been used in monorepos with millions of lines, legacy systems built over decades, and microservices across separate repositories.",
          "one-liner": "Anthropic details how Claude Code successfully integrates into large, complex enterprise codebases with millions of lines, emphasizing \"agentic search\" over RAG-based approaches and a \"harness\" of extensions.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "Anthropic's Claude Code is used in production across multi-million-line monorepos, legacy systems, and microservices for organizations with thousands of developers, supporting languages like C, C++, C#, Java, PHP. Its success relies on an \"agentic search\" approach that traverses files and uses grep, and a modular \"harness\" of tools: CLAUDE.md files for context, hooks for automation, skills for on-demand expertise, plugins for distribution, LSP integrations for symbol-level navigation, and MCP servers for internal tool connections.",
            "why": "This outlines a sophisticated approach for integrating AI coding assistants into enterprise environments, moving beyond simple API calls to a highly configurable, agent-based system that works locally and avoids common RAG scalability issues, suggesting a future where AI assistants are deeply embedded and managed like other core dev tools.",
            "takeaway": "For teams considering AI coding assistants, particularly in large codebases, establishing clear CLAUDE.md context files, scoping operations to subdirectories, and actively maintaining configurations will be crucial for effective adoption."
          },
          "deep-summary": "* Claude Code's \"agentic search\" directly navigates the file system (like a human engineer) using tools like grep, rather than relying on a centralized, often outdated, codebase index built via RAG.\n* This agentic approach works locally on the developer's machine, eliminating the need to upload or maintain a server-side index.\n* The \"harness\" is a crucial ecosystem built around the Claude Code model, comprising several extension points that determine its performance more than the model alone.\n* CLAUDE.md files provide session-specific context, like project conventions, and are loaded additively as Claude navigates directories.\n* Hooks enable self-improving behavior, such as proposing CLAUDE.md updates or dynamically loading team-specific context.\n* Skills offer on-demand, specialized workflows and domain knowledge, loaded only when needed to conserve context space.\n* Plugins bundle skills, hooks, and MCP configurations for easy distribution across an organization, standardizing setups for new engineers.\n* LSP integrations provide symbol-level code intelligence, allowing Claude to accurately follow definitions and references across files in typed languages like C and C++.\n* MCP servers connect Claude to internal tools, data sources, and APIs, extending its reach beyond the local codebase.\n* Subagents are isolated Claude instances that handle specific tasks, splitting exploration from editing for more efficient workflows.\n* Successful deployments emphasize making the codebase navigable by keeping CLAUDE.md files lean and layered, initializing in subdirectories, and using .ignore files.\n* Active maintenance of CLAUDE.md files is necessary, as model intelligence evolves, to prevent outdated instructions from hindering newer models.\n* Organizational investment, including dedicated teams or a \"DRI\" (Directly Responsible Individual) for Claude Code management, is key for driving adoption and centralizing best practices.\n* Cross-functional working groups involving engineering, info security, and governance are recommended early on to define requirements and a rollout roadmap, especially in regulated industries.",
          "decoder": "* **Agentic search**: An AI model's ability to navigate and interact with a computing environment (like a file system) by performing actions, rather than just processing static input.\n* **RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation)**: An AI architecture where a model retrieves relevant information from a knowledge base before generating a response, commonly used for grounding LLMs.\n* **CLAUDE.md**: Context files read by Claude Code at the start of every session or when navigating a directory, providing project-specific information.\n* **Hooks**: Scripts triggered by events in Claude Code sessions, used for automation, continuous improvement, or enforcing rules.\n* **Skills**: Packaged instructions and domain knowledge that Claude Code can load on-demand for specific task types.\n* **Plugins**: Bundled skills, hooks, and MCP configurations that can be installed and distributed across an organization.\n* **LSP (Language Server Protocol) integration**: Connecting Claude Code to a language server that provides real-time code intelligence (e.g., \"go to definition,\" \"find all references\") for symbol-level navigation.\n* **MCP servers**: Servers that connect Claude Code to internal tools, data sources, and APIs within an organization.\n* **Subagents**: Isolated instances of Claude that can be delegated specific tasks, returning only the final result to the main agent.",
          "rating": 5,
          "content-template-path": "full-content/2026-05-18/ai-7"
        },
        {
          "id": "ai-8",
          "title": "Recent Developments in LLM Architectures: KV Sharing, mHC, and Compressed Attention",
          "link": "https://magazine.sebastianraschka.com/p/recent-developments-in-llm-architectures",
          "image": "https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!6wCM!,w_1200,h_675,c_fill,f_jpg,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep,g_auto/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2b841d26-5b2d-4be9-9710-d89d4f023f0c_1600x900.png",
          "source": "Sebastian Raschka",
          "tags": [
            "llm",
            "research",
            "ai",
            "performance"
          ],
          "description": "KV-cache size, memory traffic, and attention cost quickly become the main constraints as reasoning models and agent workflows keep more tokens around for longer. LLM developers are adding a growing number of architecture tricks to reduce costs. Most of the changes look like small tweaks, but some are quite intricate design changes. This article looks at these architecture changes with a focus on what changes inside the transformer block, residual stream, KV cache, and attention computation.",
          "one-liner": "Sebastian Raschka details how recent open-weight LLMs like Gemma 4 and DeepSeek V4 are employing intricate architectural changes, including KV sharing, per-layer embeddings, and compressed attention, to significantly reduce long-context costs and memory footprint.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "The article by Sebastian Raschka, PhD, covers advanced LLM architecture tweaks from April-May 2026, focusing on optimizing long-context efficiency. Gemma 4 introduces KV sharing across layers to save up to 6GB of KV cache at 128K contexts and per-layer embeddings for parameter efficiency. Laguna XS.2 uses layer-wise attention budgeting with varying query-head counts. ZAYA1-8B implements Compressed Convolutional Attention (CCA) to perform attention directly in a compressed latent space. DeepSeek V4-Pro integrates Manifold-Constrained Hyper-Connections (mHC) for a wider, more stable residual pathway and a hybrid of Compressed Sparse Attention (CSA) and Heavily Compressed Attention (HCA) to compress attention along the sequence dimension, achieving 27% of inference FLOPs and 10% of KV cache size of DeepSeek V3.2 at 1M tokens.",
            "why": "The increasing complexity of transformer blocks, with targeted optimizations like KV sharing and compressed attention, signals a clear industry focus on making LLMs more memory- and compute-efficient for ever-longer contexts, crucial for reasoning models and agent workflows, indicating a trend toward specialized and intricate designs rather than fundamental architectural shifts away from transformers.",
            "takeaway": "Developers working with long-context LLMs should investigate these advanced architectural techniques (e.g., KV sharing, compressed attention, mHC) to understand potential trade-offs and efficiency gains, especially when considering model selection or custom implementations."
          },
          "deep-summary": "* KV Sharing (Gemma 4): Gemma 4 E2B/E4B models reuse key-value (KV) tensors from earlier layers in later layers, reducing KV cache size by approximately half (e.g., 6 GB for E4B at 128K context), allowing for longer contexts with less memory.\n* Per-Layer Embeddings (PLE) (Gemma 4): Gemma 4 E2B/E4B also use PLEs to increase representational capacity without significantly increasing the main transformer stack's computational cost, by adding small layer-specific token vectors after the feed-forward branch.\n* Layer-Wise Attention Budgeting (Laguna XS.2): Laguna XS.2 distributes attention capacity unevenly across layers, assigning more query heads to sliding-window attention layers (8 per KV head) and fewer to global attention layers (6 per KV head), to optimize compute where it's most useful.\n* Compressed Convolutional Attention (CCA) (ZAYA1-8B): ZAYA1-8B uses CCA to perform attention directly in a compressed latent space, saving not only KV cache size but also attention FLOPs during prefill and training, and employs convolutional mixing for local context.\n* Manifold-Constrained Hyper-Connections (mHC) (DeepSeek V4): DeepSeek V4-Pro modifies residual connections by introducing several parallel residual streams with learned, constrained mappings (doubly stochastic matrices), widening the residual pathway for more expressiveness with minimal FLOPs overhead and increased stability.\n* Compressed Sparse Attention (CSA) and Heavily Compressed Attention (HCA) (DeepSeek V4): DeepSeek V4 combines CSA (milder sequence compression with sparse top-k selection) and HCA (heavier compression, every 128 tokens into one entry, with dense attention) to reduce sequence length, achieving significant reductions in FLOPs (27%) and KV cache size (10%) at 1M context compared to DeepSeek V3.2.\n* The overall trend is to make LLM architectures more complex and specialized within the transformer paradigm, focusing on efficiency for long contexts.\n* These changes aim to reduce memory traffic and attention costs, which are critical constraints for reasoning models and agent workflows that process longer token sequences.",
          "decoder": "* **KV cache**: The Key and Value tensors computed during the attention mechanism in transformers. Caching them prevents re-computation for subsequent tokens in a sequence, but they grow linearly with sequence length, becoming a memory bottleneck.\n* **Grouped Query Attention (GQA)**: An attention variant that shares Key and Value heads across multiple Query heads to reduce KV cache size and memory traffic compared to Multi-Head Attention (MHA).\n* **Multi-head Latent Attention (MLA)**: An attention mechanism that uses a compressed latent representation for KV tensors to reduce KV cache size, but still stores one latent entry per token.\n* **Manifold-Constrained Hyper-Connections (mHC)**: A modification to transformer residual connections that replaces a single residual stream with several parallel streams, using constrained learned mappings to improve expressiveness and stability.\n* **Compressed Sparse Attention (CSA) / Heavily Compressed Attention (HCA)**: Attention mechanisms that compress along the sequence dimension by summarizing groups of tokens into fewer, compressed KV entries, reducing the effective sequence length in the cache.",
          "rating": 5,
          "content-template-path": "full-content/2026-05-18/ai-8"
        },
        {
          "id": "ai-9",
          "title": "Lighthouse Attention",
          "link": "https://nousresearch.com/lighthouse-attention",
          "image": "https://nousresearch.com/lighthouse-attention/figure2_latency.png",
          "source": "Nous Research",
          "tags": [
            "llm",
            "research",
            "ai",
            "performance"
          ],
          "description": "Lighthouse Attention, a selection-based hierarchical attention, offers up to 17x faster forward and backward passes than standard attention models at large contexts. It utilizes FlashAttention on a dense sub-sequence, maintaining efficiency and compatibility with upstream improvements. By enabling efficient long-context training and retaining dense model competence, Lighthouse Attention achieves 1.4x to 1.7x speedup in pretraining while reducing computational costs.",
          "one-liner": "Nous Research's Lighthouse Attention, a selection-based hierarchical attention method, significantly accelerates long-context LLM pretraining by using FlashAttention on a small, dense sub-sequence, achieving up to 17x faster forward/backward passes and 1.4-1.7x end-to-end speedup.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "Lighthouse Attention is a new hierarchical attention method developed by Nous Research, detailed in arXiv:2605.06554. It pools Q, K, and V symmetrically across a multi-resolution pyramid, scores entries using parameter-free L2 norms, and selects a small, dense sub-sequence for FlashAttention. This approach avoids custom sparse attention kernels and can be resumed with standard attention (SDPA) after training, converting the model back into a competent dense-attention model without performance loss. It delivers a 1.4x to 1.7x pretraining speedup at 98K context, saving 75-106 B200-hours, and is 17x faster in forward+backward passes than standard attention at 512K context on a single B200 GPU.",
            "why": "This research addresses a critical bottleneck in large language model development: the quadratic computational cost of attention in long contexts. By cleverly combining hierarchical pooling, selection, and standard FlashAttention, Lighthouse Attention enables efficient long-context training without sacrificing the model's ability to operate as a dense attention model post-training, pointing to future trends in practical and scalable LLM pretraining.",
            "takeaway": "If you are pretraining LLMs with very long contexts, consider exploring selection-based hierarchical attention methods like Lighthouse Attention, which can offer significant speedups and resource savings while maintaining model quality."
          },
          "deep-summary": "* Lighthouse Attention is a selection-based hierarchical attention mechanism designed to accelerate long-context pretraining.\n* It offers up to 17x faster forward and backward passes compared to standard attention models at 512K context on a single B200 GPU.\n* Achieves a 1.4x to 1.7x end-to-end pretraining speedup at 98K context.\n* The method involves symmetrically pooling Queries, Keys, and Values (Q, K, V) across an L-level pyramid.\n* Per-head L2 norms are used as a parameter-free scoring function to select a small, dense sub-sequence.\n* FlashAttention is then run on this gathered dense sub-sequence, eliminating the need for custom sparse attention kernels.\n* A key design choice is \"symmetric pooling,\" where Q, K, and V are pooled by the same factor at each hierarchy level, allowing the dense attention call to be O(S^2\n* d) instead of O(N\n* S\n* d) at training time, where S is the length of the sub-sequence and N is the full sequence length.\n* The training recipe is two-staged: Stage 1 uses Lighthouse selection for most of the budget, and Stage 2 resumes with standard attention (SDPA) to convert the checkpoint back into a dense attention model.\n* Experiments validate that sparse training with Lighthouse Attention does not compromise the model's ability to use full attention at inference, matching or beating dense-from-scratch baselines at the same token budget.\n* It supports 1M-token training across 32 Blackwell GPUs using context parallelism.\n* The approach has limitations, such as not being directly applicable to autoregressive decoding due to symmetric Q/K/V pooling, and its cost is O(S^2\n* d), not strictly linear.",
          "decoder": "* **FlashAttention**: An optimized attention algorithm that speeds up transformer training and inference by reducing memory reads/writes between GPU high-bandwidth memory (HBM) and SRAM, leading to significant throughput gains.\n* **Hierarchical attention**: An attention mechanism that processes different parts of the input sequence at varying levels of granularity or importance, often by summarizing or selecting tokens in a multi-level structure.\n* **SDPA (Scaled Dot-Product Attention)**: The standard attention mechanism in transformers, where queries and keys are dot-producted, scaled, and then Softmax is applied to values.\n* **Context parallelism (CP)**: A training parallelism strategy where different GPUs process different parts of the input sequence (context), often combined with other parallelisms to handle extremely long contexts.",
          "rating": 4,
          "content-template-path": "full-content/2026-05-18/ai-9"
        },
        {
          "id": "ai-10",
          "title": "Notes on pretraining parallelisms and failed training runs",
          "link": "https://www.dwarkesh.com/p/notes-on-pretraining-parallelisms",
          "image": "https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!7OkU!,w_1200,h_675,c_fill,f_jpg,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep,g_auto/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc8ed868d-6197-4209-9d77-1b7513f1c1ae_1264x694.png",
          "source": "Dwarkesh Patel",
          "tags": [
            "ai",
            "research",
            "devops",
            "infrastructure"
          ],
          "description": "Pretraining runs often fail. This article looks at all the ways that things can go wrong and why training is such a precarious operation. The key culprits seem to be breaking causality and adding bias.",
          "one-liner": "Dwarkesh Patel explores the myriad reasons pretraining runs for large AI models frequently fail, pinpointing causality breaks and numerical biases as key culprits, and highlighting the non-obvious complexities that challenge even expert kernel engineers.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "Dwarkesh Patel discusses why LLM pretraining runs are precarious, often failing due to \"breaking causality\" and \"adding bias.\" Causality breaks occur in techniques like expert choice routing (where a token's expert allocation depends on future tokens) or token dropping, leading to training on information unavailable during inference. Numerical bias, exemplified by an original GPT-4 training bug involving FP16 precision issues in collectives like all-reduce (where summing many small gradients could lead to significant errors like 1+1...10,000 times resulting in 1024 instead of 10,000 due to rounding), is also a major problem. The article also covers pretraining parallelisms like Fully Sharded Data Parallel (FSDP) as a default and the issues that necessitate pipeline parallelism, such as comms crossover and pipeline bubbles.",
            "why": "The insights into LLM training failures underscore the immense, often subtle, engineering challenges involved in scaling AI models, suggesting that breakthroughs in AI aren't just about model size or data, but also about mastering the highly complex, non-obvious interactions within distributed training systems, implying that a robust understanding of numerical stability, parallelism, and system design is paramount.",
            "takeaway": "When debugging large-scale distributed AI training, prioritize scrutinizing potential causality violations in data handling or routing, and meticulously check numerical stability and precision issues, especially in collective operations and gradient accumulation, as these subtle bugs can compound and derail entire runs."
          },
          "deep-summary": "* LLM pretraining runs frequently fail due to issues categorized as \"breaking causality\" and \"adding bias.\"\n* **Breaking causality**: Occurs when training processes use information that would not be available during real-world inference.\n* **Expert choice routing**: In Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) models, if an expert's token allocation depends on later tokens in a batch during training, it breaks causality, potentially explaining issues in models like Llama 4.\n* **Token dropping**: Experts ignoring less strongly matched tokens can break causality if a later token's strong match causes an earlier token to be dropped, as reportedly happened with Gemini 2 Pro.\n* **Adding bias**: Bias in training data or numerical operations compounds, unlike variance which can average out.\n* **FP16 precision bug**: An early GPT-4 training run failed due to FP16 issues in all-reduce collectives. Repeatedly adding '1' in FP16 could lead to rounding errors that significantly miscalculate sums (e.g., 10,000 additions of '1' summing to 1024), severely impacting gradient accumulation.\n* The speaker believes new bespoke issues will continue to emerge at scale, making full automation of kernel writing (optimizing GPU operations) difficult due to its AGI-complete nature, contrary to the idea that it's an easily verifiable RL problem.\n* **Pretraining parallelisms**:\n* **Data Parallel (DP)**: Copies model weights across GPUs, processing parts of the batch on each, but is limited by High Bandwidth Memory (HBM) for larger models.\n* **Fully Sharded Data Parallel (FSDP)**: Each GPU stores only 1/N of a layer's parameters, all-gathers full layer parameters before computation, then discards them. It's the default due to easy overlap of compute/communication.\n* FSDP comms volume: Naive FSDP is 4x parameters (all-gather forward/backward, all-reduce on backward). Optimized FSDP (reduce-scatter for gradients) achieves 3x parameters overhead over vanilla DP.\n* **Comms crossover**: FSDP's efficiency decreases with more GPUs when communication time (which doesn't scale with GPU count) exceeds compute time (which does), necessitating pipeline parallelism.\n* **Batch size floor**: FSDP is data-parallel; if sequence length is large, the number of sequences in a batch can limit the number of GPUs you can use with pure FSDP.\n* **Pipeline parallelism**: Divides model layers across GPUs, but introduces \"bubbles\" (idle GPUs) at the start and end of batches.\n* **Challenges**: Cannot easily overlap batches in training due to gradient consolidation needs. Adds architecture constraints, making features like \"attention-to-residuals\" (where each block attends to previous layers' residuals) difficult across pipeline stages.",
          "decoder": "* **Expert routing**: In Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) models, a mechanism to determine which subset of expert networks processes a given input token.\n* **Causality (in LLM training)**: The principle that a model's prediction or processing for a given token should only depend on preceding tokens in the sequence, not future ones. Breaking this can lead to models learning from \"future\" information that isn't available during inference.\n* **FP16**: Half-precision floating-point format, using 16 bits, which offers higher memory bandwidth and lower memory usage but has a smaller dynamic range and lower precision compared to FP32 or FP64.\n* **All-reduce**: A collective communication operation in distributed computing where data from all processes is combined (e.g., summed, averaged) and the result is made available to all processes.\n* **Fully Sharded Data Parallel (FSDP)**: A distributed training strategy where model parameters, gradients, and optimizer states are sharded across multiple GPUs, reducing memory footprint per GPU.\n* **Pipeline parallelism**: A distributed training strategy where different layers or stages of a model are placed on different devices, and data flows sequentially through these stages.",
          "rating": 5,
          "content-template-path": "full-content/2026-05-18/ai-10"
        },
