          "id": "tech-3",
          "title": "A revolutionary cancer treatment could transform autoimmune disease",
          "link": "https://arstechnica.com/science/2026/05/a-revolutionary-cancer-treatment-could-transform-autoimmune-disease/",
          "image": "https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/GettyImages-538030120-1152x648.jpg",
          "source": "Ars Technica",
          "tags": [
            "research",
            "health",
            "ai"
          ],
          "description": "CAR T cell therapy was originally designed to target and wipe out cancer by reprogramming patients' immune cells. It is now being offered to patients in clinical trials for autoimmune conditions. There's still uncertainty about how well the treatment works for autoimmunity and how any benefits might last, as well as what long-term side effects might arise. Another major challenge is that the therapy can cost hundreds of thousands of dollars after accounting for hospital stays, cell engineering, and other expenses.",
          "one-liner": "CAR T cell therapy, a powerful cancer treatment, is showing striking early results in clinical trials for autoimmune diseases like MS and lupus, despite high costs and long-term uncertainties.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "Originally FDA-approved in 2017 for leukemia, CAR T cell therapy reprograms a patient's T cells to target and eliminate specific cells. It's now being tested in hundreds of clinical trials for autoimmune conditions such as multiple sclerosis (MS) and lupus, showing promising early results, including reduced need for other immunotherapies for patients in a Kyverna trial.",
            "why": "This represents a significant paradigm shift in treating autoimmune diseases, moving from chronic symptom management to a potential \"immune system reset\" by eliminating problematic B cells. The high cost (hundreds of thousands of dollars) and long-term safety questions, including potential secondary cancers, highlight the ongoing challenge of translating cutting-edge oncology treatments to broader medical applications."
          },
          "deep-summary": "* CAR T cell therapy, which reprograms a patient's immune T cells to attack specific targets, was initially approved by the FDA in 2017 for aggressive forms of leukemia.\n* Researchers are now testing CAR T in hundreds of clinical trials for various autoimmune conditions like multiple sclerosis (MS), lupus, Graves’ disease, and vasculitis.\n* The therapy works by engineering T cells to target and eliminate B cells, which are responsible for producing antibodies that mistakenly attack healthy tissues in autoimmune diseases.\n* Early results are promising; for example, a Kyverna study for stiff person syndrome showed many patients walking faster and 8 no longer needing assistive devices, with all 26 participants off other immunotherapies after 4-12 months.\n* Despite successes, challenges include significant cost (hundreds of thousands of dollars per treatment), uncertainty about the duration of benefits, and potential long-term side effects such as dangerous inflammation, temporary immunosuppression, and a rare risk of secondary cancers.\n* Physicians have gained experience managing acute side effects like inflammation, which are largely reversible.\n* Researchers are developing second and third-generation CAR T therapies, including mRNA-based approaches by companies like Cartesian Therapeutics, which aim to reduce long-term cancer risk and inflammation by being more transient.\n* Efforts are also underway to lower costs by developing \"off-the-shelf\" CAR T therapies from donor cells, potentially producing treatment for over 1,000 patients from a single donor.\n* Patient Jan Janisch-Hanzlik experienced significant improvements in her MS symptoms after receiving an off-the-shelf CAR T treatment in a 2025 trial.",
          "decoder": "* **CAR T cell therapy (Chimeric Antigen Receptor T-cell therapy)**: A type of immunotherapy that involves modifying a patient's T cells (a type of immune cell) in the lab so they can recognize and attack cancer cells or, in this new application, cells involved in autoimmune diseases.\n* **B cells**: A type of white blood cell that produces antibodies. In autoimmune diseases, B cells mistakenly produce antibodies that attack the body's own tissues.\n* **Multiple Sclerosis (MS)**: An autoimmune disease in which the immune system attacks the protective sheath (myelin) that covers nerve fibers, causing communication problems between the brain and the rest of the body.\n* **Lupus (Systemic lupus erythematosus)**: A chronic autoimmune disease that can affect many different body systems, including the joints, skin, kidneys, blood cells, brain, heart, and lungs.\n* **Stiff Person Syndrome**: A rare neurological disorder characterized by progressive stiffness and rigidity, mainly in the trunk and limbs, and heightened sensitivity to stimuli like noise, touch, and emotional distress, which can trigger muscle spasms.",
          "rating": 5,
          "content-template-path": "full-content/2026-05-18/tech-3"
        },
        {
          "id": "tech-4",
          "title": "Rubin Tracks Skyscraper-Size Asteroids, Failed Supernovas, and Interstellar Visitors",
          "link": "https://www.quantamagazine.org/rubin-tracks-skyscraper-size-asteroids-failed-supernovas-and-interstellar-visitors-20260515/",
          "image": "https://www.quantamagazine.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Rubin-and-Snowy-Cerro-Pachon-cr-NSF-DOE-Rubin-Observatory-NOIRLab-SLAC-AURA-A.-Pizarro-D-Social.jpg",
          "source": "Quanta Magazine",
          "tags": [
            "research",
            "data",
            "science",
            "astrophysics"
          ],
          "description": "The Vera C. Rubin Observatory is designed to study the universe in greater detail than ever before. It is expected to discover a million asteroids, thousands of comets, and billions of stars and galaxies in its first year alone. The facility has begun collecting preliminary images and astronomers are poring over the initial data. Scientists have already been able to make new discoveries with its first images despite the images still not being as sharp as expected and the observatory still requiring a final tuning.",
          "one-liner": "The Vera C. Rubin Observatory has begun collecting preliminary images, already leading to discoveries like superfast-rotating asteroids and interstellar comets, foreshadowing a data explosion that will transform astronomy.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "The Vera C. Rubin Observatory in Chile has started taking preliminary images, revealing 1,500 new asteroids, including the 700-meter-wide 2025 MN45 which rotates every 1.88 minutes. It also detected an interstellar comet, 3I/ATLAS, 10 days before other telescopes. Once fully operational this summer, it expects to find a million new asteroids and 250,000 supernovas annually.",
            "why": "This observatory marks a new era of \"big-data astronomy,\" where the sheer volume and rapid cadence of observations (7 million alerts and 20 terabytes of data nightly) will shift the scientific approach from targeted observation to data mining and automated discovery, potentially resolving cosmological mysteries like the Hubble tension."
          },
          "deep-summary": "* The Vera C. Rubin Observatory, located in Chile's Atacama Desert, has begun collecting preliminary images as it undergoes final tuning.\n* Originally conceived as the Dark Matter Telescope in the mid-1990s, Rubin features an 8.4-meter telescope and the world's largest digital camera.\n* In its first year alone, it's expected to discover 1 million new asteroids, thousands of comets, and billions of stars and galaxies.\n* Early data from June 2025's \"first light\" images identified 1,500 new asteroids, including 19 rapidly spinning ones.\n* One notable discovery is 2025 MN45, a 700-meter asteroid that completes a revolution every 1.88 minutes, indicating a solid structure rather than a rubble pile.\n* The observatory will also aid in detecting imminent impactor asteroids a few days in advance, allowing for observation and public alerts.\n* Rubin's automated alert system, which recently pinged 800,000 alerts in a single night during a test, will generate 7 million alerts and 20 terabytes of data nightly once the full survey begins this summer.\n* It is expected to find 250,000 Type Ia supernovas annually, which could help resolve the Hubble tension (discrepancy in the universe's expansion rate).\n* Rubin detected the interstellar comet 3I/ATLAS 10 days before other telescopes, demonstrating its capability to spot rare interstellar visitors, with expectations of finding between 5 and 500 more.\n* The observatory's photometric redshift data will map galaxies and aid in studying dark energy, dark matter, and fast radio bursts (FRBs) by determining their distances.",
          "decoder": "* **Hubble tension**: The significant discrepancy between the expansion rate of the universe measured from the early universe (cosmic microwave background) and the expansion rate measured from the local universe (supernovas and other observations).\n* **Type Ia supernova**: A type of supernova that occurs in binary star systems when a white dwarf star accretes matter from its companion, eventually exceeding a critical mass and undergoing a thermonuclear explosion. They are used as \"standard candles\" for measuring cosmic distances.\n* **Photometric redshift**: A technique to estimate the distance to celestial objects (like galaxies) by analyzing their brightness across different wavelengths of light, rather than by spectroscopy.\n* **Fast radio bursts (FRBs)**: Millisecond-duration flashes of radio waves that originate from distant galaxies, with an unknown astrophysical cause, possibly related to highly magnetized neutron stars (magnetars).",
          "rating": 4,
          "content-template-path": "full-content/2026-05-18/tech-4"
        },
        {
          "id": "tech-5",
          "title": "Zero (GitHub Repo)",
          "link": "https://github.com/vercel-labs/zero",
          "image": "https://opengraph.githubassets.com/69c5c1f1c640cb938a7a062832aec2f06a55a6f6a1511ede0a0b20ac1f3f3e15/vercel-labs/zero",
          "source": "GitHub",
          "tags": [
            "agents",
            "opensource",
            "systems-programming",
            "programming-language"
          ],
          "description": "Zero is a systems programming language for agents that provides small native tools, explicit effects, predictable memory, and structured compiler output. The language is still experimental and not stable yet, but it is in a stage where users can try it out and provide feedback. Practical examples are available for users to learn the language with.",
          "one-liner": "Vercel Labs has released Zero, an experimental agent-first systems programming language focused on explicit effects, predictable memory, and structured compiler output, designed for rapid agent learning.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "Zero is an experimental systems programming language from Vercel Labs, built for AI agents. It prioritizes learnability for agents, a deep standard library, deterministic tooling for structured diagnostics and fix plans, and predictable memory management. It's pre-1 and unstable, encouraging early user feedback.",
            "why": "This project signals a potential future direction for programming language design, where AI agents are considered primary users from day one, influencing core language features like structured compiler output and built-in tooling for debugging and repair. It reflects the increasing integration of AI into developer workflows, even at the foundational language level.",
            "takeaway": "Developers interested in the intersection of AI agents and systems programming can explore Zero's examples and provide feedback on its design principles at its GitHub repository."
          },
          "deep-summary": "* Zero is an experimental systems programming language developed by Vercel Labs, explicitly designed with AI agents as primary users.\n* Key design goals include agent-first learnability, a comprehensive standard library to reduce dependency searches, deterministic tooling, and direct, scriptable developer experience.\n* The language emphasizes regularity over syntax, favoring explicit code even if it makes it less concise for human writers.\n* Features include small native tools, explicit effects, predictable memory management, and structured compiler output designed for agents to inspect and act on.\n* Zero is currently pre-1 and intentionally unstable, with breaking changes expected as the project evolves.\n* Users are encouraged to explore examples, inspect structured output, and provide feedback.\n* Installation involves a curl script, and basic commands like `zero check`, `zero run`, `zero build`, `zero graph`, `zero size`, `zero skills get`, and `zero doctor` are available.\n* Security vulnerabilities are expected, and the project is not suitable for production systems or sensitive data, advising use in isolated environments.",
          "decoder": "* **Systems programming language**: A programming language used for writing system software, such as operating systems, utilities, and device drivers, often requiring fine-grained control over hardware and memory.\n* **Agent-first programming language**: A programming language designed with the primary user being an autonomous AI agent rather than a human developer, focusing on features that aid AI understanding, debugging, and code generation.\n* **Explicit effects**: A language design principle where side effects (like I/O or modifying state) are explicitly declared or tracked by the type system, making code behavior more predictable.\n* **Predictable memory**: Refers to language features or design choices that allow developers (or agents) to accurately anticipate memory usage and allocation patterns, often avoiding garbage collection for more control.",
          "rating": 4,
          "content-template-path": "full-content/2026-05-18/tech-5"
        },
        {
          "id": "tech-6",
          "title": "How I use LLMs as a staff engineer in 2026",
          "link": "https://www.seangoedecke.com/how-i-use-llms-in-2026/",
          "image": "https://www.seangoedecke.com/og-image.jpg",
          "source": "seangoedecke.com",
          "tags": [
            "ai",
            "agents",
            "career",
            "devops"
          ],
          "description": "Agents have gotten really good in the last fifteen months. They can now be used for real work with light supervision. AI can now be used for writing code changes, investigating and fixing bugs, research in large code bases, manual testing, and more. It still isn't suitable for writing public communications, unreviewed code, or testing UIs, but its capabilities are improving quickly.",
          "one-liner": "A staff engineer reports that AI agents have dramatically improved in the last 15 months, now handling entire code changes, bug investigations, and testing with light supervision, though human judgment remains critical.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "The author, a staff engineer, now uses AI agents (like GitHub Copilot app) for drafting almost every code change, autonomously diagnosing 80% of bugs, performing research in large codebases, and managing local setup tasks. This is a significant shift from a year ago when AI was mostly for smart autocompletion and minor tactical changes, with models like OpenAI's GPT-5.5 recently becoming acceptable for proofreading.",
            "why": "The rapid maturation of AI agents, particularly in code generation and debugging, suggests a fundamental shift in developer workflows, enabling engineers to offload more routine or complex investigative tasks. This allows staff engineers to expand their capacity for \"small pieces of work,\" though human expertise remains essential for critical judgment and guiding agent efforts.",
            "takeaway": "Evaluate current AI agent capabilities beyond simple autocompletion for tasks like entire code change drafting, bug diagnosis, and integration testing, while maintaining careful human review and supervision."
          },
          "deep-summary": "* The author, a staff engineer, notes a significant shift in AI agent capabilities over the past 15 months, evolving from occasional use to constant, lightly supervised integration into daily workflow.\n* In 2025, AI was primarily used for smart autocompletion (Copilot), tactical changes, throwaway research code, learning new topics, and last-resort bug fixes.\n* Currently, AI agents are used to produce entire Pull Requests (PRs), with the author often pushing changes after a single editing pass, though initial rejections (5-6 attempts) are common for difficult tasks.\n* The GitHub Copilot app is now heavily utilized (tens of sessions daily) for code changes, replacing open VSCode windows and the Copilot CLI.\n* Agents are highly effective for bug investigations, correctly diagnosing 80% of issues autonomously, and are particularly strong when given context across multiple repositories.\n* Human expertise remains crucial for bug-hunting, providing context, building mental models, and guiding agents away from incorrect theories.\n* The author still writes their own PR descriptions, ADRs, and public communications, believing they have a better sense of important content and wanting to signal human thought.\n* AI is used for proofreading blog posts, with OpenAI's GPT-5.5 recently becoming acceptable, though models still tend to water down arguments.\n* Agents are tasked with testing changes (e.g., generating test scripts, performing integration tests) and handling annoying local setup or troubleshooting tasks.\n* The author now considers test code cheap, allowing for more expansive and exploratory testing by agents.\n* UI testing is an exception, as agents are not trusted with subtle look-and-feel aspects.\n* The core job of shipping projects and exercising judgment remains, but AI agents have broadened the scope of \"small pieces of work\" the author can take on.\n* The key skill now is finding the right balance: utilizing agents for more work without over-trusting them for critical or public-facing tasks.",
          "decoder": "* **LLM (Large Language Model)**: An AI model trained on vast amounts of text data to understand, generate, and process human language, often used for tasks like code generation, summarization, and conversation.\n* **AI Agent**: An AI system designed to perceive its environment, make decisions, and take actions autonomously or with minimal human supervision, often by chaining LLM calls and tool usage.\n* **Staff engineer**: A senior-level engineering role in tech companies, typically focusing on technical leadership, strategy, complex problem-solving, and mentoring across multiple teams.\n* **PR (Pull Request)**: A method in software development for a developer to notify team members that they have completed a feature or bug fix and want to merge it into the main codebase, allowing for review and discussion.\n* **ADR (Architectural Decision Record)**: A document that captures a significant architectural decision, its context, the options considered, and the chosen option with its consequences.\n* **GitHub Copilot**: An AI pair programmer developed by GitHub and OpenAI that assists users by autocompleting code and suggesting entire functions in various programming languages.",
          "rating": 5,
          "content-template-path": "full-content/2026-05-18/tech-6"
        },
        {
          "id": "tech-7",
          "title": "How to enter side doors",
          "link": "https://velvetnoise.substack.com/p/how-to-enter-side-doors",
          "source": "Velvet Noise",
          "tags": [
            "career",
            "startup"
          ],
          "description": "Many people try to gain employment through the front door: they find a job advertisement, send their resume, and hope that someone on the other side notices them. Most people don't realize there are other entrances into the building. Conversations at parties, warm introductions, cold emails, and visible proof of work are viable alternatives. Sometimes, it's about creating a signal that attracts the exact person who needs it.",
          "one-liner": "Beyond traditional job applications, \"side doors\" like warm introductions, cold emails, and visible proof of work are often more effective routes to employment.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "The article suggests that instead of only applying through job advertisements, individuals should leverage networking at parties, seeking warm introductions, sending targeted cold emails, and showcasing tangible work to create opportunities.",
            "why": "This reflects an understanding that traditional hiring processes are often inefficient and that personal connections and demonstrable skills can bypass bureaucratic hurdles, particularly in competitive industries like tech and startups.",
            "takeaway": "Actively build a public portfolio or contribute to open-source projects to create visible proof of work that can attract recruiters and potential employers."
          },
          "rating": 2
        },
        {
          "id": "tech-8",
          "title": "The Sigmoids Won't Save You",
          "link": "https://www.astralcodexten.com/p/the-sigmoids-wont-save-you",
          "image": "https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!V9C0!,w_1200,h_675,c_fill,f_jpg,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep,g_auto/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa6fa0283-2093-481c-a484-dd86d2cc67cf_1024x562.png",
          "source": "Astral Codex Ten",
          "tags": [
            "ai",
            "research",
            "data"
          ],
          "description": "The idea that all exponentials eventually become sigmoids might not be necessarily true for AI. There are several examples of exponentials that don't end up becoming sigmoids (or haven't yet), for example, the decline in birth rates or solar power deployment. Things that are currently happening are more likely to continue happening than not. AI is unlikely to stop progressing on all fronts anytime soon.",
          "one-liner": "The common belief that all exponential growth eventually flattens into a sigmoid curve might not apply to AI progress, which often continues exponentially longer than predicted.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "Scott Alexander argues against the \"all exponentials become sigmoids\" talking point for AI, citing examples like declining birth rates and solar power deployment, where exponential trends persist beyond forecasters' predictions. He references a Wharton team's AI capability prediction from early 2026 that was quickly surpassed.",
            "why": "This challenges a common heuristic used to downplay rapid technological progress, particularly in AI, suggesting that inherent limits are often further away or overcome by new paradigms, making current scaling trends more likely to continue."
          },
          "deep-summary": "* The \"all exponentials eventually become sigmoids\" argument suggests that rapid growth trends will naturally flatten out due to inherent limits.\n* This argument is often used to dismiss concerns about the rapid progression of AI capabilities.\n* The author, Scott Alexander, provides examples where this prediction has failed or been continuously delayed.\n* UN birthrate projections in declining countries repeatedly forecast flattening rates that didn't materialize, with actual rates continuing to drop.\n* World Energy Organization (WEO) predictions for solar power deployment consistently underestimated growth, expecting a plateau that never came.\n* A 2026 Wharton team model predicting AI capability trajectory was swiftly invalidated by the next released AI model, which continued exponential growth.\n* The article suggests that without a deep understanding of the underlying process and its limits, assuming an exponential trend will continue (Lindy's Law) is often a better default than prematurely predicting a sigmoid.\n* AI has shown dramatic improvement since GPT-1 in 2017 (or 2019 for the \"scaling era\"), and Lindy's Law would suggest this trend continues for several more years.",
          "decoder": "* **Sigmoid curve**: An S-shaped curve that represents a phenomenon (like population growth or technological adoption) that starts with slow growth, then accelerates rapidly, and finally slows down as it approaches a maximum limit.\n* **Lindy's Law**: A heuristic that states the future life expectancy of some non-perishable thing (like a technology or an idea) is proportional to its current age. The longer it has survived, the longer it is likely to survive.",
          "rating": 4,
          "content-template-path": "full-content/2026-05-18/tech-8"
        },
        {
          "id": "tech-9",
          "title": "Native all the way, until you need text",
          "link": "https://justsitandgrin.im/posts/native-all-the-way-until-you-need-text/",
          "image": "https://justsitandgrin.im/posts/native-all-the-way-until-you-need-text/index.png",
          "source": "justsitandgrin.im",
          "tags": [
            "mobile",
            "frontend",
            "swiftui",
            "web"
          ],
          "description": "SwiftUI &amp; Apple's native SDKs are constraints when it comes to building rich text rendering for long-form chats.",
          "one-liner": "Despite nearly two decades of native macOS/iOS development, the author found Apple's native SDKs like SwiftUI and TextKit 2 severely lacking for rich text rendering in long-form chat apps.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "The author describes extensive struggles implementing Markdown support and proper text selection in a pure Swift/SwiftUI app, facing issues with performance, design limitations, and basic features like context menus. Ultimately, using WebKit or even Electron provided superior text handling and typography compared to SwiftUI, AppKit, or TextKit 2.",
            "why": "This highlights a critical deficiency in Apple's native development ecosystem for advanced text-intensive applications, suggesting that for complex UIs, web-based rendering often surpasses native tools in flexibility, feature parity, and developer experience.",
            "takeaway": "If building a macOS/iOS app with complex rich text rendering, especially for chat or document editing, seriously consider WebKit or Electron for that specific component to avoid significant development hurdles with native SDKs."
          },
          "deep-summary": "* The author, a veteran macOS/iOS developer, attempted to implement a chat app with Markdown support using pure Swift/SwiftUI.\n* SwiftUI presented issues with selection (by design) and general performance (jumpy scrolling, lags).\n* Moving to NSTextView with TextKit 2 introduced CPU spikes during streaming and poor integration with SwiftUI.\n* AppKit with NSCollectionView caused cell blinking issues (by design).\n* Even going lower-level with pure TextKit 2 had terrible streaming performance and lacked modern integrations.\n* Achieving basic native macOS text behaviors like context menus, dictionary lookup, and accessibility became a multi-month project.\n* Using WebKit to render Markdown \"mostly just works\" with good performance and typography, offering proper control.\n* The author was \"amazed\" by how well Electron handled text operations, Markdown, and typography out-of-the-box, often with better performance than pure TextKit 2.\n* The conclusion is that for rich text rendering in long-form chats, SwiftUI and native Apple SDKs become constraints, not advantages, making web-based solutions a more practical choice.",
          "decoder": "* **SwiftUI**: Apple's declarative UI framework for building apps across all Apple platforms.\n* **AppKit**: Apple's object-oriented GUI framework for macOS apps, predating SwiftUI.\n* **TextKit 2**: Apple's text layout and rendering engine for macOS and iOS, used by AppKit and SwiftUI for text components.\n* **WebKit**: Apple's browser engine used in Safari and within apps to display web content.\n* **Electron**: An open-source framework that allows developers to build desktop GUI applications using web technologies like HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, rendering them via a Chromium engine and Node.js.",
          "rating": 4,
          "content-template-path": "full-content/2026-05-18/tech-9"
        },
        {
          "id": "tech-10",
          "title": "Git Is Not Fine",
          "link": "https://www.billjings.com/posts/title/git-is-not-fine/",
          "source": "billjings.com",
          "tags": [
            "devops",
            "opensource",
            "backend",
            "version-control"
          ],
          "description": "Git has been behind the state of the art for a while now, prompting companies like Meta to develop better in-house systems.",
          "one-liner": "Git, while excellent for distributed source storage, struggles as a distributed workflow tool, especially with common patterns like stacked PRs, leading to issues with mutability and revision history tracking.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "Bill Jings argues that Git's model for handling mutable changes and tracking revision history for \"stacked PRs\" (sequential Pull Requests) is overly complex and error-prone, requiring external tools like Graphite to manage. He contrasts this with internal systems at companies like Meta that have surpassed Git's capabilities for years.",
            "why": "This reveals a fundamental limitation in Git's design that becomes apparent in modern, asynchronous development workflows, suggesting that despite its ubiquity, there's a strong need for more advanced version control systems that better model mutable changes and complex branching strategies.",
            "takeaway": "If you frequently use stacked PRs or find Git's rebase/history management frustrating, consider exploring newer version control tools or Git wrappers like 'jj' (Jujutsu) that offer a more intuitive model for mutable changes."
          },
          "deep-summary": "* Git excels as a distributed source store but falls short as a distributed workflow tool, particularly for complex, asynchronous development.\n* The article highlights pain points, especially with \"stacked PRs\" where multiple sequential changes are submitted for review concurrently.\n* Git's immutable commit model and lack of native understanding of successor commits or direct revision history make managing stacked PRs difficult and fragile.\n* Rebasing stacked PRs in Git can easily lead to accidental loss of relationships or incorrect states.\n* Tools like Graphite try to address this by building external metadata stores, but these can fall out of sync with Git itself.\n* Git's model of mutability, involving the staging area (index), unstaged changes, and HEAD, is complex and makes the \"full state\" of a repository hard to reason about.\n* The author criticizes Git for not being able to represent common workflows, such as having a workspace that combines a bugfix from one PR with work from an ongoing feature branch, while keeping them logically separate for review.\n* Large companies like Meta have developed superior in-house version control systems that address these issues, demonstrating that Git is \"behind the state of the art.\"\n* The article introduces 'jj' (Jujutsu) as a tool that aims to fix these shortcomings, implying a more intuitive and robust model for mutable history.",
          "decoder": "* **Stacked PRs (Pull Requests)**: A workflow where developers create a series of dependent commits/branches, each submitted as a separate pull request, built on top of the previous one, allowing for smaller, more manageable reviews.\n* **Rebase**: A Git operation that moves or combines a sequence of commits to a new base commit, effectively rewriting commit history.\n* **Staging area (Index)**: An area in Git where you prepare changes before committing them. It acts as a buffer between your working directory and your repository's history.\n* **HEAD**: A pointer in Git that indicates the current commit you are working on.\n* **Jujutsu (jj)**: A new version control system or Git wrapper that aims to provide a more intuitive and powerful interface for managing mutable history and complex workflows than Git.",
          "rating": 5,
          "content-template-path": "full-content/2026-05-18/tech-10"
        },
        {
          "id": "tech-11",
          "title": "I strongly believe there are entire companies right now under heavy AI psychosis",
          "link": "https://threadreaderapp.com/thread/2055380239711457578.html",
          "image": "https://threadreaderapp.com/images/screenshots/thread/2055380239711457578.jpg",
          "source": "Mitchell Hashimoto",
          "tags": [
            "ai",
            "devops",
            "enterprise"
          ],
          "description": "Changes are happening so fast that nobody is noticing the underlying architecture decaying, and people are denying that this is an issue because they are focusing on the wrong metrics.",
          "one-liner": "Mitchell Hashimoto warns that companies operating under \"AI psychosis\" are over-relying on Mean Time To Recovery (MTTR) with AI agents to fix bugs quickly, ignoring critical decay in underlying system architecture.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "Mitchell Hashimoto, co-founder of HashiCorp, observes a dangerous \"AI psychosis\" where companies prioritize rapid bug fixes via AI agents over building resilient systems. He draws parallels to the \"MTBF vs MTTR\" debate during the cloud transition, where over-automation led to systems that appeared healthy locally but were globally incomprehensible and fragile.",
            "why": "This provides a crucial warning about the potential pitfalls of blindly adopting AI for software development, highlighting the risk of optimizing for easily measurable \"fast recovery\" metrics while neglecting the fundamental health and understanding of complex systems, potentially leading to catastrophic failures.",
            "takeaway": "Review your software development metrics to ensure you're balancing Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF) and Mean Time To Recovery (MTTR), and don't let AI-driven automation mask underlying architectural decay or reduce semantic understanding of your systems."
          },
          "decoder": "* **AI psychosis**: A term coined by the author to describe a state where companies become irrationally fixated on the perceived benefits of AI, particularly in software development, to the detriment of sound engineering principles.\n* **Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)**: A metric measuring the average time between system failures, indicating reliability.\n* **Mean Time To Recovery (MTTR)**: A metric measuring the average time it takes to restore a system after a failure, indicating responsiveness to incidents.",
          "rating": 4,
          "content-template-path": "full-content/2026-05-18/tech-11"
        },
        {
          "id": "tech-12",
          "title": "Agent Hooks: Deterministic Control for Agent Workflows",
          "link": "https://nader.substack.com/p/agent-hooks-deterministic-control",
          "source": "Nader D.",
          "tags": [
            "agents",
            "devops",
            "ai"
          ],
          "description": "Hooks make agent workflows more dependable by implementing tests, policies, logs, and completion gates as deterministic parts of the workflow.",
          "one-liner": "\"Agent hooks\" introduce deterministic control into AI agent workflows by implementing tests, policies, logs, and completion gates as integral, predictable components.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "Nader D. proposes \"Agent Hooks\" as a method to make AI agent workflows more reliable. These hooks are functions that run at specific points (pre-run, post-tool use, post-completion) and can perform tasks like validation, logging, and enforcing policies, ensuring that agents adhere to desired behaviors and constraints.",
            "why": "This signifies a movement towards engineering rigor and predictability in the nascent field of AI agents, recognizing the need to impose structure and control on autonomous systems to ensure safety, reliability, and auditability in production environments.",
            "takeaway": "If developing AI agent workflows, consider implementing \"hooks\" or similar mechanisms to embed deterministic tests, policies, and logging, improving the reliability and observability of agent behavior."
          },
          "decoder": "* **Agent hooks**: Functions or scripts that are executed at predefined points in an AI agent's workflow, allowing for deterministic control, validation, logging, and policy enforcement.",
          "rating": 3
        },
        {
          "id": "tech-13",
          "title": "Uber turns on Waymo as it pours $10B+ into owning robotaxi alternatives",
          "link": "https://electrek.co/2026/05/15/uber-turns-on-waymo-10-billion-robotaxi-alternatives/",
          "source": "Electrek",
          "tags": [
            "startup",
            "mobility",
            "robotaxi"
          ],
          "description": "Waymo's rapid scaling to 400,000 rides per week proved that AV operators might not need Uber at all, so Uber is pivoting to asset ownership to avoid being cut out entirely.",
          "one-liner": "Uber is investing over $10 billion in robotaxi alternatives and partnering with third-party autonomous vehicle companies to avoid being sidelined by Waymo's rapid scaling.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "Waymo's success with 400,000 rides per week demonstrates that autonomous vehicle (AV) operators might not need Uber's platform. In response, Uber is investing more than $10 billion to own its own robotaxi alternatives and integrating third-party AV companies into its platform.",
            "why": "This highlights Uber's strategic shift from a pure platform model to a more asset-heavy approach in the autonomous vehicle space, driven by the realization that AV operators could become self-sufficient and cut out intermediaries."
