        {
          "id": "design-10",
          "title": "Your Image is Almost Right",
          "link": "https://journal.everypixel.com/your-image-is-almost-right",
          "source": "Everypixel Journal",
          "tags": [
            "ai",
            "design",
            "creative-tools"
          ],
          "description": "Mini Apps is a set of AI tools designed to fix common image production issues when assets are \"90% there\" but need quick adjustments. The two initial tools are Camera Angle Editor, which regenerates images from different perspectives without cropping or distorting, and Image Upscaler, which creates new visual detail rather than just stretching pixels. These tools are optimized for workflow acceleration and work best when approximate results are sufficient to move projects forward.",
          "one-liner": "Everypixel's new \"Mini Apps\" offer AI tools like Camera Angle Editor and Image Upscaler to quickly fix common image production issues, ideal for when assets are \"90% there.\"",
          "summary": {
            "what": "Everypixel Workroom introduced \"Mini Apps,\" a suite of AI tools designed for rapid image adjustments. The initial offerings include a Camera Angle Editor, which regenerates images from different perspectives without cropping, and an Image Upscaler that synthesizes new visual detail, moving beyond simple pixel stretching.",
            "why": "This signifies a refinement in AI creative tools, focusing on specific \"gap-filling\" functions to accelerate existing workflows rather than just generating content from scratch, making AI more practical for iterative design processes.",
            "takeaway": "If you regularly work with images that are \"almost right\" but need quick perspective changes or resolution bumps, Everypixel's Mini Apps could be a fast solution, especially where approximate results are acceptable."
          },
          "deep-summary": "* **Camera Angle Editor**: Regenerates an image from a different camera perspective, filling in previously unseen areas rather than cropping or distorting. Useful for adjusting product shots or architectural visuals.\n* **Image Upscaler**: Uses a generative AI approach to synthesize new visual detail when increasing resolution, making textures sharper and edges hold, rather than just enlarging pixels. Useful for archival photos or low-res stock images.\n* These tools are optimized for workflow acceleration and rapid iteration when \"approximate\" results are sufficient.\n* Everypixel notes that for precise identity preservation or photorealistic brand assets, working directly with generative models in their \"Picture Lab\" is recommended.\n* The Image Upscaler may alter facial features, so caution is advised for portraits where likeness accuracy is critical.",
          "decoder": "* **Generative model**: An artificial intelligence model that can create new data, such as images or text, rather than just analyzing or classifying existing data.\n* **Identity preservation**: The ability of an AI model to maintain the exact likeness or specific features of a subject (e.g., a person's face) when generating or modifying an image.\n* **Workflow acceleration**: Tools or processes designed to speed up tasks and improve efficiency in a work environment, often by automating or simplifying steps.\n* **OOH (Out-of-Home) advertising**: Advertising that reaches consumers when they are outside their homes, such as billboards, public transport ads, and digital displays.",
          "rating": 4,
          "content-template-path": "full-content/2026-05-18/design-10"
        },
        {
          "id": "design-11",
          "title": "A Designer of the World's Most Ubiquitous Symbols, the Movie",
          "link": "https://www.printmag.com/daily-heller/the-daily-heller-roger-cook/",
          "image": "https://www.printmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/symbols-2.jpg",
          "source": "PrintMag",
          "tags": [
            "design",
            "career",
            "culture",
            "policy"
          ],
          "description": "Filmmaker Valentina Canavesio is creating a documentary about Roger Cook (1930-2021), the designer behind the ubiquitous Department of Transportation symbols who remains largely unknown despite his significant contributions. The film reveals that Cook's real name was Rajie and his parents were Christian Palestinian immigrants, a heritage he reconnected with later in life, which transformed his work into social commentary about Palestinian struggles. Canavesio discovered this story through Instagram and was motivated to share this humanizing Palestinian-American immigrant story.",
          "one-liner": "Filmmaker Valentina Canavesio is creating a documentary revealing that Roger Cook, designer of ubiquitous DOT symbols, was Christian Palestinian immigrant Rajie Cook whose later art critiqued Palestinian struggles.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "Filmmaker Valentina Canavesio is producing a documentary about Roger Cook (1930-2021), known for designing the standard Department of Transportation sign symbols with Don Shanosky in 1974. Canavesio discovered Cook's birth name was Rajie, and his parents were Christian Palestinian immigrants; he later reconnected with his heritage, transforming his art into social commentary on Palestinian issues, which the film explores.",
            "why": "This reveals a hidden layer to a well-known figure in design history, highlighting how personal heritage and political context can profoundly influence an artist's later work, and bringing a humanizing Palestinian-American immigrant story to the forefront of design discourse."
          },
          "deep-summary": "* Roger Cook (1930-2021) was half of Cook &amp; Shanosky Associates, responsible for the 1974 standard Department of Transportation sign symbols.\n* Filmmaker Valentina Canavesio's documentary reveals his birth name was Rajie, and he was the son of Christian Palestinian immigrants.\n* Cook's early life involved assimilation, but he reconnected with his roots after visiting the West Bank.\n* His later art transformed into social commentary, using assemblage boxes to critique the \"apartheid status\" of Palestinians and advocate for peace.\n* The film aims to explore the intersection of family, politics, and art, bringing to light a Palestinian-American immigrant story.\n* Canavesio discovered his story via an Instagram video in December 2023, motivated by a desire to humanize Palestinian narratives.\n* The documentary is currently in post-production, raising funds via Kickstarter to finalize editing from over 50 hours of material.",
          "decoder": "* **Department of Transportation (DOT) symbols**: A standardized set of graphic symbols designed to convey information quickly and universally, often seen in public spaces like airports and roads.\n* **Hagiography**: A biography that idealizes or idolizes its subject, often emphasizing their good qualities and downplaying any flaws.\n* **Assemblage art**: A type of three-dimensional art that combines various objects, often found or everyday items, to create a new whole.\n* **Intifada**: Arabic word meaning \"shaking off,\" referring to Palestinian uprisings against Israeli occupation. The Second Intifada occurred from 2000-2005.\n* **Pratt**: Refers to Pratt Institute, a private university in New York City known for its programs in art, design, architecture, and writing.\n* **Verité**: A documentary filmmaking style that emphasizes realism and a naturalistic approach, often using handheld cameras and natural sound to create a sense of immediacy.\n* **Arab American Museum**: Refers to the Arab American National Museum, located in Dearborn, Michigan, dedicated to preserving and celebrating the history and culture of Arab Americans.",
          "rating": 4,
          "content-template-path": "full-content/2026-05-18/design-11"
        },
        {
          "id": "design-12",
          "title": "Can a new logo help Threads escape Instagram's shadow?",
          "link": "https://www.creativebloq.com/design/logos-icons/can-a-new-logo-help-threads-escape-instagrams-shadow",
          "image": "https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/8G5LP3Bro38iz2JaQcSvs7-1920-80.png",
          "source": "Creative Bloq",
          "tags": [
            "design",
            "branding",
            "social-media"
          ],
          "description": "Threads has introduced a refreshed logo and wordmark as part of an effort to establish itself as a more independent brand rather than an extension of Instagram. According to Threads' design lead Christopher Clare, the redesign replaces inherited Instagram-inspired typography with a bolder, italicized style intended to convey a more forward-looking and confident identity.",
          "one-liner": "Threads has revamped its logo and wordmark with bolder, italicized typography to shed its \"temporary\" Instagram sibling image and forge an independent, forward-looking identity.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "Threads unveiled a refreshed logo and wordmark, departing from the Instagram-inspired typography it initially used. According to Threads' head of design Christopher Clare, the new identity employs bolder, italicized lettering to convey a more distinct, confident, and \"forward-thinking\" brand image, aiming to establish itself as a standalone platform since its 2023 launch.",
            "why": "This move reflects Meta's strategic effort to differentiate Threads as a serious, independent competitor in the text-based social media space, rather than just an opportunistic offshoot of Instagram, suggesting a long-term commitment to the platform."
          },
          "deep-summary": "* Threads launched in 2023 during Twitter's rebrand to X, initially feeling like a side project of Instagram.\n* The original branding inherited typography (Instagram Sans) and design cues from Instagram, making it feel \"inherited rather than distinct\" and \"static.\"\n* Christopher Clare, Threads' head of design, announced the refresh, calling it an update for a \"new, standalone era.\"\n* The new logo and wordmark feature bolder text and an italicized style.\n* The italics are intended to convey a \"forward-thinking energy\" and momentum, aligning with conversations on Threads.\n* The increased weight helps the logo stand out from Instagram and other app icons.\n* The redesign is an attempt to establish Threads as a more sure-footed and independent brand, differentiating it from its Meta siblings.",
          "decoder": "* **Wordmark**: A distinct text-only typographic logo used to identify a company, organization, or product.\n* **Typography**: The art and technique of arranging type to make written language legible, readable, and appealing when displayed.\n* **Instagram Sans**: The proprietary typeface developed and used by Instagram across its brand and products.\n* **Meta**: The parent company of Facebook, Instagram, WhatsApp, and Threads.",
          "rating": 3,
          "content-template-path": "full-content/2026-05-18/design-12"
        },
        {
